> - **Topic:** Union Types

<!-- SECTION_1_START -->
## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Academic Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

A **Union** in C is a user-defined data type that allows the storage of **different data types in the same memory location**. It is a heterogeneous aggregate type whose members share a single, common storage region, meaning only **one member can contain a valid value at any given time**. The size of a union is determined by the size of its **largest member** (plus any padding required by the compiler for alignment).

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Board Definition:** A union is a derived data type that provides a way to store different types of data in the same memory location. Unlike structures, where each member has its own distinct memory, union members **overlap** in memory. The total storage allocated is sufficient to hold the largest member type.

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

> [!NOTE]
> **Real-World Analogy: A Single Parking Garage Slot**
> Imagine a parking spot in a multi-purpose garage. At different times of the day, the same spot can be occupied by a **motorcycle** (small), a **car** (medium), or a **truck** (large). However, **only ONE vehicle can occupy that spot at a time**. The size of the spot is built to fit the **largest** possible vehicle (the truck), but it does not waste space by creating separate slots for each type. This is precisely how a union works — it allocates memory equal to its **largest member** and lets you interpret that memory in different ways depending on which "vehicle" (member) you last parked there.

### 1.3 General Syntax of a Union

```c
union UnionTag {
    member1_declaration;
    member2_declaration;
    member3_declaration;
    ...
};
```

### 1.4 Key Highlights

- **Single Shared Memory:** All members share the same starting address.
- **Mutually Exclusive Values:** Writing to one member overwrites the others.
- **Size Rule:** `sizeof(union) = max(sizeof(member1), sizeof(member2), ...)` + padding.
- **Declaration vs Definition:** Declaring a union creates the type; defining a variable allocates actual memory.
- **Anonymous Unions (C11):** A union declared without a tag name, allowing direct member access.
<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

### 2.1 Operational Mechanics — "How a Union Works"

A union works on the principle of **memory overlap**. Let us break down the operational logic step-by-step:

- **Step 1: Type Definition** — When you declare a union, the compiler calculates the size required to hold the **largest** member. This size is the total storage footprint of any variable of that union type.
- **Step 2: Memory Allocation** — Upon defining a union variable (e.g., `union Data d;`), the compiler allocates a contiguous block of memory whose size equals that of the largest member.
- **Step 3: Writing to a Member** — Assigning a value to a member writes the bit pattern into the shared memory starting from the same base address.
- **Step 4: Reading from a Member** — Reading from a member interprets the underlying bit pattern according to that member's type. If a different member was last written, the result is **type-punned** (re-interpreted) data.
- **Step 5: End of Life** — When the union variable goes out of scope, the entire shared memory block is released.

### 2.2 The "Why" — Engineering Utility of Unions

| Use Case | Engineering Utility |
|----------|-------------------|
| **Variant Records** | Store data that can be of multiple types (e.g., a token in a compiler that can be an `int`, `float`, or `string`). |
| **Memory-Constrained Systems** | Critical in **embedded systems** where RAM is limited (microcontrollers often have <64 KB RAM). |
| **Hardware Register Access** | Used to access the same memory address as different data types (e.g., a 32-bit register as four 8-bit bytes). |
| **Type Punning** | Reinterpret the bit pattern of one type as another (e.g., inspecting the byte representation of a `float`). |
| **Protocol Parsing** | Network/communication protocols where a packet field can carry different data depending on context. |
| **Tagged Unions (Discriminated Unions)** | Combined with a struct holding a "tag" field to safely track which member is currently valid. |

### 2.3 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| Property | Rule / Formula | Notes |
|----------|---------------|-------|
| Size of Union | `sizeof(union U) = max(sizeof(m1), sizeof(m2), ...)` | Plus padding for alignment |
| Member Address | `&u.m1 == &u.m2 == &u` | All members share the same base address |
| Active Member Rule | Only the **last written** member holds a valid value | Other members contain stale/overwritten data |
| Union vs Struct Size | `sizeof(union) ≤ sizeof(struct with same members)` | Union is always smaller or equal |
| Union in Array | `union U arr[10]; sizeof(arr) = 10 * sizeof(union U)` | Standard array multiplication |
| Alignment Padding | `sizeof(union) = max(member_size) rounded up to alignment` | E.g., a union with a `double` is 8-byte aligned on 64-bit systems |
| Nested Union | `sizeof(outer) ≥ sizeof(inner_union)` | Recursive application of max rule |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Critical KTU Distinction:** In a **structure**, members are laid out sequentially with each getting its own memory. In a **union**, all members start at the **same offset (zero)** and overlap. This is the single most-tested concept in KTU board exams for this topic.

### 2.4 Comparison: Union vs Structure

| Feature | Structure (`struct`) | Union (`union`) |
|---------|--------------------|-----------------| 
| Memory | Sum of all member sizes (sequential) | Size of largest member (overlapping) |
| Member Access | All members simultaneously valid | Only one member valid at a time |
| Keyword | `struct` | `union` |
| Total Size | Larger (often) | Smaller or equal |
| Use Case | Grouping related but distinct data | Reinterpreting same memory differently |
| Padding | Compiler inserts for alignment | Same alignment rules apply |
<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
## 3. Step-by-Step Derivations, Code Analysis & Numerical Examples

### 3.1 Exhaustive Analysis: Memory Size Calculation

**Problem:** Determine the total size of the following union on a typical 64-bit system (8-byte alignment):

```c
union Data {
    int    i;       // 4 bytes
    float  f;       // 4 bytes
    double d;       // 8 bytes
    char   c;       // 1 byte
    char   name[20]; // 20 bytes
};
```

**Step-by-Step Solution:**

**Step 1:** Identify the size of each member.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{sizeof}(i) &= 4 \text{ bytes} \\
\text{sizeof}(f) &= 4 \text{ bytes} \\
\text{sizeof}(d) &= 8 \text{ bytes} \\
\text{sizeof}(c) &= 1 \text{ byte} \\
\text{sizeof}(\text{name}) &= 20 \text{ bytes}
\end{aligned}
$$

**Step 2:** Apply the **max rule** to find the largest member.

$$
\text{Largest member} = \max(4, 4, 8, 1, 20) = 20 \text{ bytes (name)}
$$

**Step 3:** Apply alignment. Since the largest naturally-aligned member is `double` (8 bytes), the compiler ensures the union's start address is 8-byte aligned. The size of 20 bytes is already a multiple of 4 but not 8. The compiler will round it up.

$$
\text{sizeof(union Data)} = 20 \text{ bytes} \quad \text{(No padding needed since } 20 \% 8 = 4, \text{ but } 20 \% 4 = 0\text{)}
$$

On a typical 64-bit GCC compiler, this union occupies **20 bytes** (the compiler does not pad the union to 24 bytes because the natural alignment of the largest member that requires strict alignment here is `double`, but union size is determined by the largest member's size, not its alignment requirement in most practical cases).

> [!NOTE]
> **Compiler Behavior Note:** In practice, `sizeof(union Data)` will be **20 bytes** on GCC/Clang. The alignment requirement of the union equals the strictest alignment among its members (8 for `double`), but the **size** is governed by the largest member.

### 3.2 Step-by-Step Code Trace

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>

union Data {
    int    i;
    float  f;
    char   str[20];
};

int main() {
    union Data data;

    data.i = 42;
    printf("data.i  = %d\n", data.i);
    printf("data.f  = %f\n", data.f);  // Garbage: same bytes reinterpreted

    data.f = 3.14f;
    printf("\nAfter writing to data.f:\n");
    printf("data.i  = %d\n", data.i);   // Garbage: overwritten
    printf("data.f  = %f\n", data.f);

    strcpy(data.str, "Hello");
    printf("\nAfter writing to data.str:\n");
    printf("data.i  = %d\n", data.i);   // Garbage
    printf("data.f  = %f\n", data.f);   // Garbage
    printf("data.str = %s\n", data.str);

    printf("\nSizeof(union Data) = %lu\n", sizeof(union Data));
    printf("Address of i   = %p\n", &data.i);
    printf("Address of f   = %p\n", &data.f);
    printf("Address of str = %p\n", &data.str);

    return 0;
}
```

**Memory Trace (after `strcpy(data.str, "Hello")`):**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Byte 0} &= 'H' = 0x48 \\
\text{Byte 1} &= 'e' = 0x65 \\
\text{Byte 2} &= 'l' = 0x6C \\
\text{Byte 3} &= 'l' = 0x6C \\
\text{Byte 4} &= 'o' = 0x6F \\
\text{Byte 5} &= '\0' = 0x00 \\
\text{Bytes 6-19} &= \text{undefined (stale data)}
\end{aligned}
$$

When you read `data.i` now, the first 4 bytes (`0x48 0x65 0x6C 0x6C`) are interpreted as an `int`. On a little-endian system, this is `0x6C6C6548 = 1819043144` — clearly garbage. This is why **only the last-written member is reliable**.

### 3.3 Tagged Union (Discriminated Union) — Type-Safe Pattern

To safely use unions, the professional practice is to **wrap** the union in a struct with a "tag" field that tracks the active member.

```c
#include <stdio.h>

enum Type { TYPE_INT, TYPE_FLOAT, TYPE_STRING };

struct Variant {
    enum Type tag;
    union {
        int    i;
        float  f;
        char   s[32];
    } value;
};

void printVariant(struct Variant v) {
    switch (v.tag) {
        case TYPE_INT:    printf("Integer: %d\n", v.value.i); break;
        case TYPE_FLOAT:  printf("Float:   %f\n", v.value.f); break;
        case TYPE_STRING: printf("String:  %s\n", v.value.s); break;
    }
}
```

**Memory Layout Trace:**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{sizeof}(\text{enum Type}) &= 4 \text{ bytes (typically)} \\
\text{sizeof}(\text{union}) &= 32 \text{ bytes (largest is } s[32]\text{)} \\
\text{sizeof}(\text{struct Variant}) &= 4 + 32 = 36 \text{ bytes (plus padding)}
\end{aligned}
$$

The **tag** field ensures the program knows which member of the union to read safely, eliminating the ambiguity of "which member is currently active?"

### 3.4 Anonymous Union (C11 Feature)

```c
struct Message {
    enum { MSG_INT, MSG_FLOAT } type;
    union {
        int   ival;
        float fval;
    };  // No name — anonymous union
};

int main() {
    struct Message m = { .type = MSG_INT, .ival = 100 };
    printf("ival = %d\n", m.ival);  // Direct access, no .value. prefix
}
```

> [!NOTE]
> Anonymous unions are particularly popular in **Linux kernel code** and **embedded firmware** for clean hardware register definitions.
<!-- SECTION_3_END -->

<!-- SECTION_4_START -->
## 4. Structural Diagrams & Schematics

### 4.1 Memory Layout Comparison: Union vs Structure

```mermaid
graph TB
    subgraph STRUCT["STRUCTURE: struct Example {int i; float f; char c;}"]
        S1["Offset 0-3: int i (4 bytes)"]
        S2["Offset 4-7: float f (4 bytes)"]
        S3["Offset 8: char c (1 byte)"]
        S4["Offset 9-11: Padding (3 bytes)"]
        S5["Total: 12 bytes"]
        S1 --> S2 --> S3 --> S4 --> S5
    end

    subgraph UNION["UNION: union Example {int i; float f; char c;}"]
        U1["Offset 0-3: SHARED MEMORY"]
        U2["  - int i interprets 4 bytes"]
        U3["  - float f interprets 4 bytes"]
        U4["  - char c interprets 1 byte"]
        U5["Total: 4 bytes (largest member)"]
        U1 --> U2
        U1 --> U3
        U1 --> U4
        U1 --> U5
    end

    style STRUCT fill:#ffe6e6,stroke:#cc0000,stroke-width:2px
    style UNION fill:#e6f3ff,stroke:#0066cc,stroke-width:2px
```

### 4.2 Block-Level Functional Architecture of Union Memory Access

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    A[Program writes to<br/>union member X] --> B{X is which type?}
    B -->|int| C[Write 4 bytes<br/>starting at offset 0]
    B -->|float| D[Write 4 bytes<br/>starting at offset 0]
    B -->|char[]| E[Write N bytes<br/>starting at offset 0]
    C --> F[Shared Memory Block<br/>size = max member]
    D --> F
    E --> F
    F --> G[Program reads<br/>union member Y]
    G --> H{X equals Y?}
    H -->|Yes| I[Valid interpreted value]
    H -->|No| J[Undefined / Type-Punned Result]

    style A fill:#fff4cc,stroke:#cc9900
    style F fill:#ccf2ff,stroke:#0099cc,stroke-width:3px
    style I fill:#ccffcc,stroke:#009900
    style J fill:#ffcccc,stroke:#cc0000
```

### 4.3 Tagged Union (Discriminated Union) Flow

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    Start([New Variant Data]) --> SetTag[Set tag field<br/>to indicate type]
    SetTag --> SetVal[Write value to<br/>appropriate union member]
    SetVal --> Store[Store struct in<br/>memory / container]
    Store --> ReadLater[Later: Read struct]
    ReadLater --> CheckTag{Tag value?}
    CheckTag -->|TYPE_INT| ReadI[Read union.i<br/>as integer]
    CheckTag -->|TYPE_FLOAT| ReadF[Read union.f<br/>as float]
    CheckTag -->|TYPE_STRING| ReadS[Read union.s<br/>as string]
    ReadI --> Output([Safe Output])
    ReadF --> Output
    ReadS --> Output

    style Start fill:#e6f3ff,stroke:#0066cc
    style CheckTag fill:#fff4cc,stroke:#cc9900,stroke-width:2px
    style Output fill:#ccffcc,stroke:#009900,stroke-width:2px
```

### 4.4 Union Lifecycle in a Program

```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> Declared: union Data d;
    Declared --> Writing: d.i = 10;
    Writing --> Reading: value = d.i;
    Reading --> Writing: d.f = 3.14;
    Writing --> Reading: val = d.f;
    Reading --> Destroyed: End of scope
    Destroyed --> [*]

    note right of Writing: Writing to one member<br/>INVALIDATES all others
    note right of Reading: Only valid if same<br/>member was last written
```
<!-- SECTION_4_END -->

