## 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

---

### 5.1 Part A Questions (3 Marks Each)

---

**Q1. [KTU University Exam – May 2024]**
**Define a union in C. How is it different from a structure in terms of memory allocation?**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

A **union** is a user-defined data type in C that allows multiple members of different types to share the same memory location.

**Memory Allocation Difference:**

| Aspect | Structure | Union |
|--------|-----------|-------|
| Memory | Each member has its own separate memory (sum of sizes) | All members share the same memory (size of largest member) |
| Simultaneous Values | All members can hold valid values at the same time | Only one member holds a valid value at a time |
| Total Size | Larger (sum of members) | Smaller (largest member only) |

**Example:**
```c
struct S { int i; float f; };   // Size = 8 bytes (4+4)
union  U { int i; float f; };   // Size = 4 bytes (max)
```

---

**Q2. [KTU University Exam – Dec 2023]**
**What is the output of the following C program? Justify your answer.**

```c
#include <stdio.h>
union Test {
    int  x;
    char y[4];
};
int main() {
    union Test t;
    t.x = 0x41424344;
    printf("%c %c %c %c\n", t.y[0], t.y[1], t.y[2], t.y[3]);
    return 0;
}
```

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

The output is: **`D C B A`**

**Justification:** The integer `0x41424344` is stored in memory. On a **little-endian** system (which is the standard for x86/x64 processors), the least significant byte is stored first. Therefore:
- `t.y[0]` = `0x44` = `'D'`
- `t.y[1]` = `0x43` = `'C'`
- `t.y[2]` = `0x42` = `'B'`
- `t.y[3]` = `0x41` = `'A'`

This demonstrates **type punning** — the same memory is interpreted as 4 separate `char` values instead of one `int`.

> [!NOTE]
> On a big-endian system, the output would be `A B C D`. This is a classic KTU trick question.

---

### 5.2 Part B Questions (14 Marks Each — Internal Choice)

---

### **Question A (14 Marks) [KTU University Exam – June 2024]**

**(a)** Explain the concept of **unions** in C with a suitable example. Discuss how memory is allocated for union members. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Write a C program using a **tagged union** to represent a shape that can be either a `circle` (with radius) or a `rectangle` (with length and breadth). Compute and display the area based on the shape type. **(7 marks)**

---

#### Model Solution — Part (a) [7 marks]

**Definition:** A union is a user-defined data type in C where all members share the **same memory location**. The size of a union equals the size of its **largest member**, because at any given time, only one member can hold a meaningful value.

**Memory Allocation Logic:**
- The compiler allocates a single block of memory equal to the size of the largest member.
- All members start at the **same offset (0)** within this block.
- Writing to one member overwrites the bytes of all other members.

**Code Example (2 marks):**
```c
#include <stdio.h>
union Number {
    int   i;
    float f;
    char  c;
};

int main() {
    union Number n;
    n.i = 65;
    printf("i = %d, c = %c\n", n.i, n.c);  // c prints 'A' (ASCII 65)
    n.f = 3.14f;
    printf("f = %f, i = %d\n", n.f, n.i);  // i prints garbage
    printf("Size: %lu bytes\n", sizeof(n));  // 4 bytes
    return 0;
}
```

**Memory Diagram (2 marks):**
```
Offset:  0   1   2   3
       [ i (4 bytes)   ]  ← shared
       [ f (4 bytes)   ]  ← shared
       [ c ][...........]  ← only first byte used
```

**Key Points (2 marks):**
- Only the **last-written** member contains a valid value.
- `sizeof(union) = max(sizeof(all members))` + alignment padding.
- All members have the **same address**: `&n.i == &n.f == &n.c == &n`.

---

#### Model Solution — Part (b) [7 marks]

```c
#include <stdio.h>

enum ShapeType { CIRCLE, RECTANGLE };

struct Shape {
    enum ShapeType type;
    union {
        struct {
            float radius;
        } circle;
        struct {
            float length;
            float breadth;
        } rectangle;
    } data;
};

float computeArea(struct Shape s) {
    if (s.type == CIRCLE) {
        return 3.14159f * s.data.circle.radius * s.data.circle.radius;
    } else {
        return s.data.rectangle.length * s.data.rectangle.breadth;
    }
}

int main() {
    struct Shape s1 = { CIRCLE, { .circle = {5.0f} } };
    struct Shape s2 = { RECTANGLE, { .rectangle = {4.0f, 6.0f} } };

    printf("Area of Circle (r=5.0)   = %.2f\n", computeArea(s1));
    printf("Area of Rectangle (4x6)  = %.2f\n", computeArea(s2));

    return 0;
}
```

**Output:**
```
Area of Circle (r=5.0)   = 78.54
Area of Rectangle (4x6)  = 24.00
```

**Explanation:** The `enum ShapeType` acts as the **tag** that tells the program which union member is currently valid. The union itself stores either circle or rectangle data, saving memory compared to storing both fields separately.

---

### **Question B (14 Marks) [KTU University Exam – Dec 2023]**

**(a)** Differentiate between **structure** and **union** in C with examples. Explain the concept of **anonymous unions** with a code snippet. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Write a C program that uses a union to **interpret the bytes of a floating-point number** and determine whether the system is **little-endian or big-endian**. **(7 marks)**

---

#### Model Solution — Part (a) [7 marks]

**Structure vs Union Comparison Table (4 marks):**

| Feature | Structure | Union |
|---------|-----------|-------|
| Keyword | `struct` | `union` |
| Memory | Sum of all member sizes | Size of largest member |
| Member Access | All members simultaneously | Only one at a time |
| Total Size | Always ≥ sum of members | Always ≤ size of largest |
| Use Case | Grouping related data | Variant data / memory saving |

**Code Examples (1 mark):**
```c
struct S { int i; float f; };   // 8 bytes
union  U { int i; float f; };   // 4 bytes
```

**Anonymous Unions (2 marks):**
An anonymous union is a union declared without a tag name, allowing its members to be accessed directly from the enclosing struct. Introduced in **C11**.

```c
#include <stdio.h>
struct Sensor {
    int id;
    union {
        int   intVal;
        float floatVal;
        char  strVal[20];
    };  // anonymous — no .member suffix needed
};

int main() {
    struct Sensor s = { .id = 101, .intVal = 42 };
    printf("ID=%d, Value=%d\n", s.id, s.intVal);

    struct Sensor t = { .id = 102, .floatVal = 3.14f };
    printf("ID=%d, Value=%f\n", t.id, t.floatVal);
    return 0;
}
```

---

#### Model Solution — Part (b) [7 marks]

```c
#include <stdio.h>

union EndianTest {
    unsigned int  i;
    unsigned char c[4];
};

int main() {
    union EndianTest u;
    u.i = 0x01020304;

    printf("Integer stored: 0x%08X\n", u.i);
    printf("Bytes in memory: %02X %02X %02X %02X\n",
           u.c[0], u.c[1], u.c[2], u.c[3]);

    if (u.c[0] == 0x01) {
        printf("System is BIG-ENDIAN\n");
    } else {
        printf("System is LITTLE-ENDIAN\n");
    }

    return 0;
}
```

**Sample Output (on little-endian x86 system):**
```
Integer stored: 0x01020304
Bytes in memory: 04 03 02 01
System is LITTLE-ENDIAN
```

**Explanation (2 marks):** The integer `0x01020304` is stored in 4 bytes. The union allows us to read those same 4 bytes as individual `char` values. If the first byte (`c[0]`) is the **least significant** byte (`0x04`), the system is little-endian. If it's the most significant byte (`0x01`), the system is big-endian. This is a classic application of **type punning via unions**.

---

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Pitfalls — Where Students Lose Marks:**
> 1. **Confusing `sizeof(struct)` with `sizeof(union)`:** Students often write that union size is the *sum* of members. This is **wrong** — it is the *maximum* size.
> 2. **Assuming all members are valid simultaneously:** A common mistake is to assign values to multiple union members and expect all to retain their values. The **last write wins**, and earlier values are corrupted.
> 3. **Ignoring padding:** When calculating union size, students must account for **alignment padding** (e.g., a union with a `double` on 64-bit systems is 8-byte aligned).
> 4. **Forgetting the `union` keyword:** Writing `struct` instead of `union` in declarations is a frequent syntax error that costs marks.
> 5. **Not mentioning the same address:** The fact that `&u.m1 == &u.m2 == &u` is a **high-yield point** for full marks.
> 6. **Skipping the tag in discriminated unions:** When implementing tagged unions, students must include the **discriminator/tag** field — a union alone is not type-safe.

---

### 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Rapid Revision Checklist — Union Types**

- **Definition:** A union is a user-defined type where all members share the **same memory location**.
- **Size Formula:** `sizeof(union) = max(sizeof(each member))` + alignment padding.
- **Same Address Rule:** `&u.m1 == &u.m2 == &u` for all members `m1, m2, ...` of union `u`.
- **Mutually Exclusive:** Only the **last-written** member is valid; others are corrupted/garbage.
- **Structure vs Union:** Structure = sum of sizes; Union = max of sizes.
- **Anonymous Union (C11):** A union without a tag name; members accessible directly from the enclosing struct.
- **Tagged/Discriminated Union:** A struct wrapping a union with a `tag` field to track the active member — essential for **type safety**.
- **Type Punning:** Reinterpreting the bit pattern of one type as another (e.g., inspecting bytes of a `float` or detecting endianness).
- **Keyword:** `union` (not `struct`).
- **Use Cases:** Embedded systems (memory saving), hardware register access, variant data, protocol parsing, compiler symbol tables.
- **Common Mistake:** Reading a union member that was **not** the last one written yields **undefined behavior** (in practice, garbage).
- **Initialization:** Only the **first member** of a union can be initialized directly: `union Data d = {42};` initializes `d.i`.
- **Pointer to Union:** `union Data *p = &d;` Access members via `p->i`, `p->f`, etc.
- **Array of Unions:** `union Data arr[100];` — useful for heterogeneous data collections.
- **Nested Unions:** Unions inside structures and vice versa are fully supported.
- **Standard Reference:** Defined in **ISO C11 §6.7.2.1** (and C99/C18 with similar semantics).
- **Big-Endian vs Little-Endian:** Union-based byte inspection is the standard technique to detect endianness.
- **Compiler Padding:** `sizeof` may return a value larger than the largest member due to alignment. Always verify with `printf("%lu\n", sizeof(u))`.
