# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Classification of Overloadable Operators

Operators in C++ fall into distinct categories, each with specific overloading rules:

### 2.1.1 Unary Operators
Operate on a **single operand**. Examples: `+`, `-`, `*` (dereference), `&` (address-of), `!`, `~`, `++`, `--`, type-cast operators.

### 2.1.2 Binary Operators
Operate on **two operands**. Examples: `+`, `-`, `*`, `/`, `%`, `<<`, `>>`, `<`, `>`, `<=`, `>=`, `==`, `!=`, `&&`, `||`, `=`, `+=`, `-=`, `[]`, `()`.

### 2.1.3 Special / Member-Only Operators
A small set **must** be overloaded as **member functions**, not as `friend`/non-member functions:
- `operator=`
- `operator()`
- `operator[]`
- `operator->`

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The assignment operator `=` and the function call operator `()` **cannot be inherited** and **must be member functions** of the class. This is a recurring KTU two-mark question.

## 2.2 The Two Implementation Strategies

There are exactly **two** ways to implement an overloaded operator in C++:

| Strategy | When to Use | Signature Form | Access to Private Data |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Member Function** | When the operator naturally modifies the *left-hand* operand's state. | `return_type operator op (const RightType& rhs)` | Direct (implicit `this`) |
| **Friend Function** | When the operator is **symmetric** between LHS and RHS (e.g., `obj + 5` and `5 + obj`). | `friend return_type operator op (const LeftType& lhs, const RightType& rhs)` | Requires `friend` declaration |

## 2.3 Operators That **CANNOT** Be Overloaded

> [!WARNING]
> The KTU board loves this. The following operators are **not overloadable**:
> 1. `.` (member access)
> 2. `.*` (pointer-to-member access)
> 3. `::` (scope resolution)
> 4. `?:` (ternary conditional)
> 5. `sizeof` (size operator)
> 6. `#` and `##` (preprocessor tokens, technically not operators in C++)

## 2.4 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| Category | Rule | Formula / Syntax |
|---|---|---|
| Member Function Form | Binary `op` | `T operator+(const T& rhs) const;` |
| Friend Function Form | Binary `op` | `friend T operator+(const T& a, const T& b);` |
| Unary Prefix `++` | Member | `T& operator++();` |
| Unary Postfix `++` | Member | `T operator++(int);` |
| Stream Insertion `<<` | Friend only (recommended) | `friend ostream& operator<<(ostream& os, const T& obj);` |
| Stream Extraction `>>` | Friend only (recommended) | `friend istream& operator>>(istream& is, T& obj);` |
| Assignment `=` | Member only | `T& operator=(const T& rhs);` |
| Subscript `[]` | Member only | `T& operator[](size_t i);` |
| Function Call `()` | Member only | `R operator()(P1, P2, ...);` |
| Const-ness of `this` | For read-only ops, append `const` | `T operator+(const T& rhs) const;` |
| **Precedence Preservation** | Always | `*` stays higher than `+` after overloading |
| **Arity Preservation** | Always | Unary stays unary, binary stays binary |

## 2.5 Real-World Engineering Utility

In **Signal Processing** libraries, a `Complex` class overloads `+`, `-`, `*`, `/` so engineers write:
$$z = z_1 \cdot z_2 + z_3$$
just as they would in textbooks, instead of verbose function calls like `z = add(multiply(z1, z2), z3)`. This **syntactic sugar** dramatically improves code readability in DSP, control systems, and finite-element analysis toolchains.

