# 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Exhaustive Walkthrough — Overloading `+` for a `Complex` Class

We will derive the **complete, compilable** implementation step by step. The goal: make the expression `c1 + c2` produce a `Complex` sum.

### Step 1 — Class Declaration
We first declare a `Complex` class with real and imaginary parts, and a parameterized constructor.

```cpp
class Complex {
private:
    float real;
    float imag;
public:
    Complex(float r = 0.0f, float i = 0.0f) : real(r), imag(i) {}
    // ... operator to be added ...
};
```

**Logic explanation:** The constructor uses default arguments so that `Complex()` is equivalent to `Complex(0, 0)`, and `Complex(3.5)` gives `imag = 0`. This is required for the implicit conversions that allow `c1 + 2.0f` to compile.

### Step 2 — Declare the Overloaded Operator
The `+` operator, when applied to two `Complex` objects, must return a **new** `Complex` (it does not modify the existing ones). Hence the return type is `Complex`, not `Complex&`.

```cpp
Complex operator+(const Complex& other) const;
```

**Logic explanation:**
- `const Complex& other` — passed by const reference to **avoid copy** and to **prevent modification** of the right-hand operand.
- The trailing `const` after the parameter list — promises this function will **not modify the left-hand operand** (`*this`).

### Step 3 — Define the Operator
The body constructs a temporary `Complex` and returns it.

```cpp
Complex Complex::operator+(const Complex& other) const {
    Complex temp;
    temp.real  = this->real + other.real;
    temp.imag  = this->imag + other.imag;
    return temp;
}
```

**Logic explanation:** The standard mathematical definition of complex addition is:
$$z_1 + z_2 = (a_1 + a_2) + i(b_1 + b_2)$$

### Step 4 — Full Compilation Matrix

Putting it all together for the KTU board-style answer:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Complex {
    float real, imag;
public:
    Complex(float r = 0, float i = 0) : real(r), imag(i) {}
    Complex operator+(const Complex& obj) const;
    void display() const {
        cout << real << " + i" << imag;
    }
};

Complex Complex::operator+(const Complex& obj) const {
    Complex temp;
    temp.real = real + obj.real;
    temp.imag = imag + obj.imag;
    return temp;
}

int main() {
    Complex c1(3.0, 4.0), c2(1.5, 2.5);
    Complex c3 = c1 + c2;
    c3.display();   // Output: 4.5 + i6.5
    return 0;
}
```

### Step 5 — Trace the Expression

$$
c_1 = 3.0 + 4.0i, \quad c_2 = 1.5 + 2.5i
$$

$$
c_3 = c_1 + c_2
$$

By operator overloading, the compiler expands `c1 + c2` to `c1.operator+(c2)`.

The evaluation flow:

$$
c_3.\text{real} = c_1.\text{real} + c_2.\text{real} = 3.0 + 1.5 = 4.5
$$

$$
c_3.\text{imag} = c_1.\text{imag} + c_2.\text{imag} = 4.0 + 2.5 = 6.5
$$

## 3.2 Exhaustive Walkthrough — Unary Postfix `++`

A classic KTU board trap: distinguishing prefix from postfix.

### Step 3.2.1 — The "Dummy `int`" Rule

The compiler differentiates prefix from postfix by a single, dummy `int` parameter:

| Form | Signature | Behavior |
|---|---|---|
| **Prefix** `++x` | `T& operator++();` | Increment, then return new value. |
| **Postfix** `x++` | `T operator++(int);` | Save old value, increment, return **old** value. |

### Step 3.2.2 — Implementation

```cpp
class Counter {
    int value;
public:
    Counter(int v = 0) : value(v) {}

    // Prefix: returns reference to self
    Counter& operator++() {
        ++value;
        return *this;
    }

    // Postfix: returns old value by copy
    Counter operator++(int) {
        Counter temp = *this;  // save old state
        ++value;               // increment
        return temp;           // return OLD
    }

    int get() const { return value; }
};
```

### Step 3.2.3 — Trace

```cpp
Counter c(5);
Counter a = ++c;  // c becomes 6, a becomes 6
Counter b = c++;  // c becomes 7, b becomes 6 (old value)
```

**Logic explanation:**
- In `++c`, the prefix version is called, increments `c` first, then returns `*this` by reference, which is bound to `a`.
- In `c++`, the postfix version is called. The `int` parameter is just a syntactic flag — it receives no actual value. A copy of the *old* `c` is returned, so `b` gets `6` while `c` itself becomes `7`.

## 3.3 Exhaustive Walkthrough — Stream Insertion `<<`

You **cannot** make `<<` a member of your class, because the left operand of `<<` is `ostream` (a system class you don't own). It **must** be a non-member, typically a `friend`.

```cpp
class Student {
    string name;
    int roll;
public:
    Student(string n, int r) : name(n), roll(r) {}
    friend ostream& operator<<(ostream& os, const Student& s);
};

ostream& operator<<(ostream& os, const Student& s) {
    os << "Roll: " << s.roll << ", Name: " << s.name;
    return os;
}
```

> [!NOTE]
> Returning `ostream&` (a **reference**, not a copy) is what enables **chaining**: `cout << s1 << s2 << s3;`. If we returned `ostream` by value, the second `<<` would operate on a *temporary* stream, which is non-portable.

## 3.4 Analytical Matrix — Operator Selection Guide

| Operator | Member / Friend | Returns | Why |
|---|---|---|---|
| `+`, `-`, `*`, `/` | Either | New object (`T`) | Does not modify LHS. |
| `+=`, `-=`, `*=`, `/=` | Member (recommended) | `T&` | Modifies LHS in place. |
| `==`, `!=`, `<`, `>` | Either | `bool` | Comparison. |
| `<<`, `>>` (streams) | Friend | `ostream&` / `istream&` | LHS is system type. |
| `=` (assignment) | Member only | `T&` | Mandatory. |
| `[]` (subscript) | Member only | `T&` or `const T&` | Mandatory. |
| `()` (functor) | Member only | depends | Mandatory. |
| `->` (arrow) | Member only | `T*` | Mandatory. |
| `*` (dereference) | Member | `T&` | Iterators. |
| `++`, `--` | Member | See above | Dummy int distinguishes prefix/postfix. |

