### Q1. [KTU University Exam — May 2024]
**What is operator overloading? List any four operators that cannot be overloaded in C++.**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

Operator overloading is a compile-time polymorphism feature in C++ that allows programmers to redefine the meaning of existing operators (like `+`, `-`, `<<`, etc.) for user-defined data types (classes and structures), enabling objects to be used in expressions just like fundamental types. The precedence, associativity, and arity of the operator remain unchanged.

The four operators that **cannot** be overloaded are:
1. `.` (member access / dot operator)
2. `.*` (pointer-to-member access)
3. `::` (scope resolution operator)
4. `?:` (ternary conditional operator)

