### Question A (14 Marks) — [KTU University Exam — June 2024]

**(a)** Design a `Time` class with `hours`, `minutes`, and `seconds` as integer members. Overload the `+` operator to add two `Time` objects with proper carry propagation. Write the complete C++ program and demonstrate with an example. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Explain why `operator<<` cannot be overloaded as a member function. Overload `operator<<` for the `Time` class defined in part (a) to display the time in `HH:MM:SS` format. **(7 marks)**

#### Model Solution

**Part (a) — 7 marks:**

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Time {
    int hr, min, sec;
public:
    Time(int h = 0, int m = 0, int s = 0) : hr(h), min(m), sec(s) {}

    Time operator+(const Time& t) const {
        Time temp;
        temp.sec  = sec + t.sec;
        temp.min  = min + t.min + (temp.sec / 60);
        temp.sec %= 60;
        temp.hr   = hr + t.hr + (temp.min / 60);
        temp.min %= 60;
        return temp;
    }

    void display() const {
        cout << hr << ":" << min << ":" << sec;
    }
};

int main() {
    Time t1(2, 45, 50), t2(1, 30, 25);
    Time t3 = t1 + t2;
    cout << "Sum = ";
    t3.display();
    return 0;
}
```

**Trace:**
$$t_1 = 2 \text{ h } 45 \text{ m } 50 \text{ s}, \quad t_2 = 1 \text{ h } 30 \text{ m } 25 \text{ s}$$

Add seconds: $50 + 25 = 75 \Rightarrow 1$ min $15$ s carry.  
Add minutes: $45 + 30 + 1 = 76 \Rightarrow 1$ h $16$ min carry.  
Add hours: $2 + 1 + 1 = 4$ h.

$$t_3 = 4 \text{ h } 16 \text{ m } 15 \text{ s}$$

**Output:** `Sum = 4:16:15`

*(2 marks — class + constructor, 3 marks — overloaded + with carry logic, 2 marks — main + trace.)*

**Part (b) — 7 marks:**

**Why `operator<<` cannot be a member function (3 marks):**

In the expression `cout << t1`, the left-hand operand is `cout`, which is an object of class `ostream` defined inside the C++ standard library. Since the programmer does not own or modify the `ostream` class, the `operator<<` cannot be added as a member of `ostream`. Therefore, it must be implemented as a **non-member function**, typically declared as a `friend` of the user's class so that it can access the private members `hr`, `min`, `sec`.

Additionally, returning `ostream&` (a reference) allows **chaining** of stream insertions like `cout << t1 << t2;`.

**Overloaded `operator<<` (4 marks):**

```cpp
class Time {
    // ... existing members ...
    friend ostream& operator<<(ostream& os, const Time& t);
};

ostream& operator<<(ostream& os, const Time& t) {
    if (t.hr   < 10) os << "0";
    os << t.hr << ":";
    if (t.min  < 10) os << "0";
    os << t.min << ":";
    if (t.sec  < 10) os << "0";
    os << t.sec;
    return os;
}
```

**Sample call:**
```cpp
Time t(4, 16, 15);
cout << t;   // Output: 04:16:15
```

