### Question B (14 Marks) — [KTU University Exam — June 2024] *(Alternative to Question A)*

**(a)** Explain the concept of operator overloading. List the rules and restrictions of operator overloading in C++. Mention any three operators that must be overloaded as member functions. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Design a `Vector3D` class with `x`, `y`, `z` float members. Overload the following:
- The `*` operator to compute the **dot product** of two vectors.
- The unary `-` operator to compute the **negation** of a vector.  
Write the complete C++ program. **(7 marks)**

#### Model Solution

**Part (a) — 7 marks:**

**Concept (2 marks):** Operator overloading is a compile-time polymorphism technique in C++ that allows the programmer to extend the meaning of existing operators to user-defined types (classes). This makes user-defined types behave syntactically like built-in types, improving code readability and reusability.

**Rules and Restrictions (3 marks):**
1. Only **existing** operators can be overloaded; new operators cannot be invented.
2. The **arity** (number of operands) of the operator cannot be changed.
3. The **precedence** and **associativity** of the operator cannot be altered.
4. At least one operand must be a **user-defined type**.
5. Operators like `.`, `.*`, `::`, `?:`, `sizeof` **cannot** be overloaded.
6. Overloaded operators follow the same **syntax rules** (e.g., `a + b` requires `a` on the left).
7. Overloaded operators **cannot have default arguments**.

**Three member-only operators (2 marks):**
1. `operator=` (assignment)
2. `operator[]` (subscript)
3. `operator()` (function call / functor)

*(Acceptable: `operator->`.)*

**Part (b) — 7 marks:**

The dot product of two 3D vectors is:
$$\vec{A} \cdot \vec{B} = A_x B_x + A_y B_y + A_z B_z$$

The unary negation returns $(-x, -y, -z)$.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Vector3D {
    float x, y, z;
public:
    Vector3D(float a = 0, float b = 0, float c = 0) : x(a), y(b), z(c) {}

    // Dot product
    float operator*(const Vector3D& v) const {
        return x * v.x + y * v.y + z * v.z;
    }

    // Unary negation
    Vector3D operator-() const {
        return Vector3D(-x, -y, -z);
    }

    void display() const {
        cout << "(" << x << ", " << y << ", " << z << ")";
    }
};

int main() {
    Vector3D v1(1, 2, 3), v2(4, 5, 6);
    cout << "v1 = "; v1.display(); cout << endl;
    cout << "v2 = "; v2.display(); cout << endl;
    cout << "Dot product = " << (v1 * v2) << endl;   // 32
    Vector3D v3 = -v1;
    cout << "-v1 = "; v3.display(); cout << endl;    // (-1, -2, -3)
    return 0;
}
```

**Trace:** $1 \cdot 4 + 2 \cdot 5 + 3 \cdot 6 = 4 + 10 + 18 = 32$.

*(2 marks — class + constructor, 2 marks — dot product, 2 marks — unary negation, 1 mark — main and trace.)*

