## 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!NOTE]
> **Rapid Revision Checklist — KTU 2024 Module 2: Overloaded Operators**

- **Operator overloading** = compile-time polymorphism; gives new meaning to existing operators for user-defined types.
- **Syntax:** `return_type operator<symbol>(parameters) { body }`.
- **Cannot invent** new operators; cannot change **arity, precedence, or associativity**.
- **At least one operand must be a user-defined type** (otherwise overload has no effect).
- **Member-only operators** (must be members): `=`, `[]`, `()`, `->`.
- **Non-overloadable operators**: `.`, `.*`, `::`, `?:`, `sizeof`.
- **Member function form:** `T operator op (const T& rhs) const;` — has implicit `this`.
- **Friend function form:** `friend T operator op (const T& a, const T& b);` — used when LHS is a system type (e.g., `ostream`) or when symmetric.
- **Stream operators `<<` and `>>`** must be non-member (`friend`) and must return `ostream&` / `istream&` for chaining.
- **Assignment `=`** must be a member and return `T&` to allow `a = b = c`.
- **Prefix `++`** signature: `T& operator++();` — increments then returns self.
- **Postfix `++`** signature: `T operator++(int);` — saves old, increments, returns old.
- **Default arguments are NOT allowed** in overloaded operator functions.
- **Always pass user-defined operands by const reference** to avoid unnecessary copies.
- **Tricky cases:** `c1 + c2` ↔ `c1.operator+(c2)` (member) or `operator+(c1, c2)` (friend). Operator function name resolution is done by the compiler based on operand types.
- **Real-world use:** `Complex`, `BigInteger`, `Matrix`, `Vector3D`, `String`, `Time`, `Date`, custom iterators.
- **Common KTU trap:** "Distinguish between overloading `<<` as a friend vs as a member." Answer: *must be a friend (non-member) because LHS is `ostream`, which you cannot modify.*

