## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

### 2.1 The "Why" Behind Studying Multiple Languages

Advanced programming is **not** about knowing many syntaxes — it is about understanding **how a language's design choices affect**:

1. **Type Safety** — Compile-time vs. runtime checking.
2. **Memory Model** — Manual (C++) vs. Garbage-Collected (Java/Python).
3. **Abstraction Cost** — How much *hidden work* the compiler/interpreter does.
4. **Expressiveness** — Lines of code needed for the same logic.

### 2.2 KTU High-Yield Comparison Sheet

| Feature | **C++** | **Java** | **Python** |
|---|---|---|---|
| Typing Discipline | Static, strong | Static, strong (with type erasure) | Dynamic, strong |
| Compilation | Compiled to native | Compiled to bytecode (JVM) | Interpreted (CPython) |
| Memory Mgmt | Manual + RAII | Automatic (GC) | Automatic (GC + refcount) |
| Multiple Inheritance | Allowed (with virtual base) | Not allowed (uses interfaces) | Allowed (via mixins/MRO) |
| Generics | Templates (compile-time) | Generics (type erasure) | Duck typing (no formal generics) |
| Lambda Support | C++11 onwards (`[](){}`) | Java 8 onwards (`()->{}`) | Built-in (`lambda x: x*2`) |
| Exception Model | Checked + unchecked | Checked + unchecked | Unchecked only |
| Header / Module | `#include` | `import` | `import` |
| Standard Output | `std::cout` | `System.out` | `print()` |

> [!NOTE]
> **Big-O Cheat Sheet for Language Operations** (must-know for KTU)
>
> $$\begin{aligned} T_{\text{list\_append}}(n) &= O(1) \text{ amortized} \\ T_{\text{dict\_lookup}}(n) &= O(1) \text{ average} \\ T_{\text{array\_traverse}}(n) &= O(n) \\ T_{\text{binary\_search}}(n) &= O(\log n) \end{aligned}$$
>
> These complexities are **language-agnostic** but their constant factors differ (Python dict uses open-addressing → higher constant than Java `HashMap`).

### 2.3 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **Embedded Systems** → C++ (manual memory, deterministic latency).
- **Enterprise Web Backends** → Java (JVM maturity, Spring ecosystem).
- **Data Science / ML Prototyping** → Python (NumPy, scikit-learn).
- **Cross-platform GUI** → C++ (Qt) or Java (JavaFX).
- **Scientific Computing** → C++ (performance) + Python (glue).

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Pitfall:** Students often confuse *paradigm* with *language*. **Java is not purely OOP** (it has primitives, `static`); **C++ is multi-paradigm** (procedural + OOP + generic + functional). Examiners test this distinction.

