## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

### 2.1 The Three Pillars of an Encapsulation Construct

1. **Data Members (Attributes)** — variables describing the object's state.
2. **Member Functions (Methods)** — functions defining the object's behavior.
3. **Access Specifiers (Visibility Modifiers)** — rules governing who can see what.

---

### 2.2 Access Specifiers in C++ (KTU High-Yield)

| Specifier | Same Class | Derived Class | Outside Class | Friend |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| `private` | ✅ Visible | ❌ Hidden | ❌ Hidden | ✅ Visible |
| `protected` | ✅ Visible | ✅ Visible | ❌ Hidden | ✅ Visible |
| `public` | ✅ Visible | ✅ Visible | ✅ Visible | ✅ Visible |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Default access in `class` is `private`**, but **default access in `struct` is `public`**. This is a classic KTU one-mark question!

---

### 2.3 Friend Constructs (Advanced Encapsulation Mechanism)

Sometimes strict encapsulation prevents legitimate access. C++ provides an *opt-out* mechanism:

- **`friend function`** — A non-member function granted access to a class's private members.
- **`friend class`** — An entire class granted access to another's private members.

> [!WARNING]
> **Friend breaks encapsulation locally but is used sparingly** (e.g., operator overloading between two classes). KTU may ask: *"Does friend violate encapsulation?"* — The correct answer is: *It bends it intentionally, not violates it permanently.*

---

### 2.4 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| Construct | Syntax | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| Class declaration | `class ClassName { ... };` | Bundles data + methods |
| Private specifier | `private:` | Default visibility inside class |
| Protected specifier | `protected:` | For inheritance hierarchies |
| Public specifier | `public:` | External interface |
| Getter (Accessor) | `T getX() const;` | Read-only access |
| Setter (Mutator) | `void setX(T v);` | Write access with validation |
| Friend function | `friend void foo();` | External privileged access |
| Friend class | `friend class Bar;` | Class-level privileged access |
| Nested class | `class Outer { class Inner{}; };` | Logical grouping helper |
| Static member | `static int count;` | Class-level shared state |
| `this` pointer | `return *this;` | Self-reference for chaining |

> [!NOTE]
> **Mathematical Intuition:** Encapsulation can be modeled as a **set-closure operation**.
> $$\text{Visible}(o) = \bigcup_{s \in S(o)} \text{Specifier}(s)$$
> where $S(o)$ is the set of all access requests to object $o$, and the union is taken over the specifier rules. Only requests matching a permitted specifier pass through the "interface gatekeeper."

---

### 2.5 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **Embedded Systems (IoT):** A `Sensor` class hides raw ADC register values behind `getTemperature()` public method.
- **Banking Software:** `Account` class hides `balance`; external code can only call `deposit()` / `withdraw()` with validation.
- **Game Engines:** `Player` class hides `healthPoints` behind setters that enforce $\text{health} \in [0, 100]$.
- **Automotive (AUTOSAR):** ECU software modules encapsulate CAN bus signals behind calibrated interfaces.
